response:
Good — I can now see the exact bug. Here is the precise diagnosis and all fixes:

---

## Diagnosis

The SCSS has **three independent failures** that together allow the logo to wrap, despite the partial fix already present:

**Failure 1 — `.navInner` lacks `flex-wrap: nowrap`.**
The flex container uses `display: flex` without an explicit `flex-wrap` declaration. The default is `nowrap`, but browsers treat this as a hint, not a hard constraint — and more importantly, the *absence of the explicit declaration* means a future property addition (or browser quirk) could silently allow wrapping. It should be explicit.

**Failure 2 — `.logo` has `flex-shrink: 0` but is still an `inline-flex` container with no `white-space: nowrap` at its own level.**
`white-space: nowrap` only lives on `.logoText`. The `.logo` element itself is `display: inline-flex` — if the browser's flex algorithm ever gives the logo container a computed width smaller than `logoMark + gap + logoText`, the two children (`logoMark` + `logoText`) can line-wrap *inside the inline-flex row* because `flex-wrap` is not explicitly set on `.logo` either. The logo mark and logo text are two flex children; without `flex-wrap: nowrap` on `.logo`, they can theoretically stack under aggressive squeeze.

**Failure 3 — `.links` has `min-width: 0` but no `flex-shrink` override.**
`min-width: 0` alone tells the browser the links container *can* shrink to zero, but without explicitly setting `flex-shrink: 1` (or larger) on `.links`, the flex algorithm may distribute shrink pressure *proportionally* between the logo and the links rather than directing all of it to the links side. The logo needs to be declared `flex-shrink: 0` (already done) **and** the links need to explicitly absorb all remaining pressure with `flex-shrink: 1`.

**Root cause: AP-066** — *Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text.* The anti-pattern was catalogued from FB-146 but wasn't yet upgraded to capture the **priority hierarchy rule**: that identity chrome (logo/name) has absolute layout priority and all other nav elements must be the absorbing layer. The principle exists in the user's mental model but not in the codified documentation.

---

## Fix

### `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);

  &::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    height: 10px;
    transform: translateY(100%);
    backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
}

.navInner {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: nowrap;          // ← ADD: explicit guard; the default is nowrap but
                              //   declaring it here makes the intent unambiguous and
                              //   prevents a future property from silently re-enabling wrapping.
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  max-width: $elan-container-wide;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);

  @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
    padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
  }
}

.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  flex-wrap: nowrap;          // ← ADD: prevents logoMark + logoText from stacking inside
                              //   the logo container when the browser squeeze-allocates
                              //   less width than (logoMark + gap + logoText).
  align-items: center;
  gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;
  text-decoration: none;
  // IDENTITY PRIORITY RULE (AP-066): The logo is the site's core identity line.
  // It has absolute layout priority in the nav row. It must NEVER wrap, collapse,
  // shrink, or move to a second line under any viewport squeeze. The correct
  // overflow response is for everything else in the nav (tagline, links) to
  // absorb the pressure — never the logo.
  flex-shrink: 0;             // ← KEEP: zero flex-shrink; logo never yields width to siblings.
  white-space: nowrap;        // ← ADD: belt-and-suspenders at the container level in case
                              //   a future child loses its own nowrap declaration.
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    .logoMark {
      background-color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }

    .logoText {
      color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }
  }
}

.logoMark {
  display: inline-block;
  height: calc($portfolio-type-2xl * 1.2);
  aspect-ratio: 1;
  flex-shrink: 0;
  background-color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  mask-image: url('/images/yg-logo.svg');
  mask-size: contain;
  mask-repeat: no-repeat;
  @include transition-fast;
}

.logoText {
  font-family: $portfolio-font-serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-2xl;
  font-weight: $portfolio-weight-regular;
  line-height: $portfolio-leading-snug;
  color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  letter-spacing: $portfolio-tracking-tight;
  white-space: nowrap;        // ← KEEP: text-level guard retained.
  @include transition-fast;
}

.links {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--portfolio-spacer-3x);
  // ABSORBING LAYER (AP-066): The links/tagline container is the nav's soft edge.
  // It must absorb ALL squeeze pressure that the logo refuses. This requires both
  // min-width: 0 (allows shrinking below intrinsic content width) AND flex-shrink: 1
  // (explicitly assigns it as the sole compression target in the flex row).
  min-width: 0;
  flex-shrink: 1;             // ← ADD: explicit; makes this the designated squeeze absorber
                              //   now that the logo holds flex-shrink: 0.
}

.link {
  font-family: var(--portfolio-font-sans);
  font-size: var(--portfolio-type-sm);
  font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-regular);
  color: var(--portfolio-text-secondary);
  text-decoration: none;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
  }
}

.linkActive {
  color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
  font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-medium);
}

.tagline {
  @include body-sm;
  color: var(--portfolio-text-secondary);
  // SOFT EDGE: The tagline yields to narrow viewports by wrapping onto up to two
  // lines. It must never clip, truncate mid-word with ellipsis, or push the logo.
  // Two-line cap prevents it from invading the site content below the nav.
  min-width: 0;
  text-align: right;
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
  line-clamp: 2;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

---

### `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — Amend AP-066

Find the existing `## AP-066` block and replace it with this upgraded version. The category index header line for Navigation & Menus stays the same (AP-066 is already listed). Only the body of the entry changes:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** A nav row uses `display: flex` without explicitly assigning compression roles to each child — the logo/identity element can shrink or wrap because no child is declared as the designated absorbing layer.

**Why it's wrong:** In a flex row, the browser distributes squeeze pressure proportionally across all children unless you explicitly forbid it on specific children. A logo or site-name element that wraps to two lines under viewport squeeze is a branding failure — not a layout inconvenience. It signals to the visitor that the interface was not deliberately designed. Identity elements are non-negotiable fixtures; they have no flex elasticity to offer.

**The priority hierarchy rule:**
Every nav row has two semantic tiers that must receive different CSS treatment:

| Tier | Element | Flex behavior | Wrap behavior |
|------|---------|---------------|---------------|
| **Identity (rigid)** | Logo mark, site name, any core brand text | `flex-shrink: 0` + `white-space: nowrap` on both the text element AND its container | Never wraps. Ever. At any viewport width. |
| **Soft edge (absorbing)** | Tagline, nav links, secondary labels | `flex-shrink: 1` + `min-width: 0` | Allowed to wrap, shrink, or line-clamp. Absorbs ALL pressure the identity tier refuses. |

**Correct alternative — three-property lock for identity elements:**
```scss
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;       // Never yields width to siblings
  flex-wrap: nowrap;    // Children cannot stack inside the container
  white-space: nowrap;  // Belt-and-suspenders: text cannot break to a new line
}
```

**Correct alternative — absorbing layer for soft-edge elements:**
```scss
.links {
  flex-shrink: 1;   // Designated compression target
  min-width: 0;     // Can shrink below intrinsic content width
}

.tagline {
  min-width: 0;
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;      // Two-line cap prevents nav height explosion
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

**What is NOT allowed to soften the identity:**
- `flex-shrink` any value other than `0` on the logo or its wrapper
- `flex-wrap: wrap` on the logo container (allows logoMark + logoText to stack)
- Removing `white-space: nowrap` from logoText "to save space on mobile"
- Any media query that relaxes the identity tier's nowrap at narrow widths

**Occurred:** FB-146. See also FB-150 (company names in experience column — same priority hierarchy logic applied to a list context).

**Frustration caused:** 1 round. The partial fix (flex-shrink: 0 on logo, nowrap on logoText only) was insufficient because it left the logo's flex container unwrapped and the links container without an explicit flex-shrink absorber.
```

