```

---

## What Each Change Does and Why

| Change | File | Mechanism |
|--------|------|-----------|
| `flex-wrap: nowrap` on `.navInner` | Navigation.module.scss | Explicit declaration makes the no-wrap intent unambiguous; prevents future property additions from silently re-enabling row wrapping. |
| `flex-wrap: nowrap` on `.logo` | Navigation.module.scss | Stops the browser from stacking `.logoMark` and `.logoText` inside the logo's own flex container when it's squeezed below their combined natural width. This is the **primary missing fix** — `flex-shrink: 0` on the logo only prevents the logo from yielding width to siblings; it does nothing to prevent the logo's own children from wrapping internally. |
| `white-space: nowrap` on `.logo` | Navigation.module.scss | Belt-and-suspenders at the container level. If any future child loses its individual `nowrap` declaration, the container-level rule prevents a regression. |
| `flex-shrink: 1` on `.links` | Navigation.module.scss | Explicitly designates the links container as the sole compression absorber. Previously `min-width: 0` alone didn't fully communicate to the flex algorithm that this container should absorb *all* remaining pressure. |
| AP-066 upgraded | design-anti-patterns.md | Codifies the **identity priority hierarchy rule** — the mental model the user just articulated — so no future agent can miss it. The old entry described a symptom (flex-shrink missing); the new entry describes the principle (two semantic tiers with different compression roles). |

---

## Principle

**AP-066 — Identity Priority Hierarchy.** A nav row is not a symmetric flex layout. It contains two semantically different tiers: identity chrome (rigid, zero elasticity) and supporting content (soft, full elasticity). The CSS must encode this asymmetry explicitly. `flex-shrink: 0` on the logo is necessary but not sufficient — you also need `flex-wrap: nowrap` on the logo's own container (to prevent its children from stacking internally) and `flex-shrink: 1` + `min-width: 0` on every sibling that must absorb the refused pressure. Identity elements have no negotiating position at any viewport width. The tagline is allowed to wrap; the name is not.
